<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Single specimen (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Laetmonice stet. CCZ _ 060 A in situ image B ventral surface C elytra on dorsal surface D harpoon-shaped chaeta E dorsal surface F neurochaeta with fringed tips G notochaetal spine shafts. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 0.5 cm (B, E). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, E), Drennan (C, D, F, G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716329" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3A</figureCitation>
). Body short, ovoid, flattened ventrally and somewhat arched dorsally. Specimen ~ 1 cm at widest point and 2 cm long, with 31 chaetigers. Dorsal felt not present. Specimen caked dorsally in dense layer of pale sediment (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Laetmonice stet. CCZ _ 060 A in situ image B ventral surface C elytra on dorsal surface D harpoon-shaped chaeta E dorsal surface F neurochaeta with fringed tips G notochaetal spine shafts. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 0.5 cm (B, E). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, E), Drennan (C, D, F, G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716329" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3B, E</figureCitation>
), easily removed from dorsum but adhering to prostomium, parapodia, chaetae, and pygidium, obscuring respective features. Elytra 15 pairs, semi-translucent, smooth, and overlapping to cover dorsum (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Laetmonice stet. CCZ _ 060 A in situ image B ventral surface C elytra on dorsal surface D harpoon-shaped chaeta E dorsal surface F neurochaeta with fringed tips G notochaetal spine shafts. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 0.5 cm (B, E). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, E), Drennan (C, D, F, G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716329" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3C</figureCitation>
). Dorsal cirri long, fine and tapering, extending beyond parapodia. Ventrum smooth. Ventral cirri, short, mostly broken off, not extending to base of neurochaetae. Parapodia biramous. Notochaetae include long, dark, brassy spines (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Laetmonice stet. CCZ _ 060 A in situ image B ventral surface C elytra on dorsal surface D harpoon-shaped chaeta E dorsal surface F neurochaeta with fringed tips G notochaetal spine shafts. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 0.5 cm (B, E). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, E), Drennan (C, D, F, G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716329" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3E</figureCitation>
) with simple, tapered tips or with harpoon-shaped tips bearing four or five recurved fangs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Laetmonice stet. CCZ _ 060 A in situ image B ventral surface C elytra on dorsal surface D harpoon-shaped chaeta E dorsal surface F neurochaeta with fringed tips G notochaetal spine shafts. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 0.5 cm (B, E). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, E), Drennan (C, D, F, G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716329" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3D</figureCitation>
); both types of notochaetae with tuberculated shafts (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Laetmonice stet. CCZ _ 060 A in situ image B ventral surface C elytra on dorsal surface D harpoon-shaped chaeta E dorsal surface F neurochaeta with fringed tips G notochaetal spine shafts. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 0.5 cm (B, E). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, E), Drennan (C, D, F, G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716329" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3G</figureCitation>
); neurochaetae include finer, shorter, paler chaetae with subdistal lateral spur and distal fringe of filamentous hairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Laetmonice stet. CCZ _ 060 A in situ image B ventral surface C elytra on dorsal surface D harpoon-shaped chaeta E dorsal surface F neurochaeta with fringed tips G notochaetal spine shafts. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 0.5 cm (B, E). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A), Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, E), Drennan (C, D, F, G)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716329" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3F</figureCitation>
), tips frequently broken off or covered in sediment.
</paragraph>
